solutions.content:
# Intuition
The problem requires constructing a binary search tree (BST) from a given preorder traversal of its nodes. The code uses a recursive approach to build the BST by dividing the problem into smaller subproblems.

# Approach
1. The bstFromPreorder function takes the given preorder traversal as input.
2. It creates a copy of the preorder traversal and sorts it to obtain the inorder traversal. This is done to determine the left and right subtrees of each node.
3. It initializes the start index for the preorder traversal as 0 and calls the build function.
4. The build function takes the preorder traversal, inorder traversal, start index, and the range of indices to process as input.
5. In the build function:
        - The base case checks if the start index exceeds the end index, indicating that there are no more nodes to process. In this case, it returns NULL.
        - It creates a new node with the value at the current start index.
        - It searches for the index of the current node's value in the inorder traversal.
        - It increments the start index to process the next node in the preorder traversal.
        - It recursively builds the left and right subtrees by calling the build function with the appropriate ranges of indices.
        - Finally, it returns the root node of the constructed subtree.
6. The build function is called recursively to construct the entire binary search tree.
7. The constructed binary search tree is returned as the result.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
The overall time complexity is O(n log n + n) = O(n log n).

- Space complexity:
The overall space complexity is O(n + n) = O(n).

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    // Helper function to search for an element in the given vector
    int search(vector<int>& in, int t) {
        for (int i = 0; i < in.size(); i++) {
            if (in[i] == t)
                return i;
        }
        return -1;
    }

    // Recursive function to build a binary tree from preorder and inorder traversals
    TreeNode* build(vector<int>& pre, vector<int>& in, int& start, int ins, int ine) {
        // Base case: When the start index exceeds the end index, there are no more nodes to process
        if (ins > ine)
            return NULL;

        // Create a new node with the value at the current start index
        TreeNode* root = new TreeNode(pre[start]);

        // Find the index of the current node in the inorder traversal
        int ind = search(in, pre[start]);

        // Increment the start index to process the next node in the preorder traversal
        start++;

        // Recursively build the left and right subtrees
        root->left = build(pre, in, start, ins, ind - 1);
        root->right = build(pre, in, start, ind + 1, ine);

        // Return the root node of the binary tree
        return root;
    }

    // Function to construct a binary search tree from a preorder traversal
    TreeNode* bstFromPreorder(vector<int>& pre) {
        // Create a copy of the preorder traversal
        vector<int> in = pre;

        // Sort the copy to obtain the inorder traversal
        sort(in.begin(), in.end());

        // Start index for the preorder traversal
        int start = 0;

        // Build the binary tree recursively using the preorder and inorder traversals
        return build(pre, in, start, 0, in.size() - 1);
    }
};

