solutions.content:
Nice one that we can do with the quick reminder that items in a BST go so that the smaller ones go on the left, the bigger ones all on the right.

We will then add a few extra parameters to our function signature to help us with recursion:
* `st` is where we we will be start considering values in `preorder`, defaulted to `0`;
* `ed` is where we we will be stop considering values in `preorder (excluded)`, defaulted to `-1`.

Inside our function, we will:
* correct `ed` when it equals `-1`, setting it to be `preorder.size()` (ie: past the last element);
* have a base case for our recursion - when `st >= ed`, we will just `return` `NULL`;
* compute the proper value of `md`, setting it to be the first element that is `> preorder[st]`)
* finally, return a `TreeNode` with
	* value equal to `root->val`;
	* a `left` node equal to a recursive call to  `bstFromPreorder` moving from `st + 1` to `md`;
	* a `right` node equal to a recursive call to  `bstFromPreorder` moving from `md` to `ed`.

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    TreeNode* bstFromPreorder(vector<int>& preorder, int st = 0, int ed = -1) {
        // updating ed for the first run
        if (ed == -1) ed = preorder.size();
        // end case
        if (st >= ed) return NULL;
        // support variables
        int md = st;
        while (md < ed && preorder[st] >= preorder[md]) md++;
        return new TreeNode(preorder[st++], bstFromPreorder(preorder, st, md), bstFromPreorder(preorder, md, ed));
    }
};
```

Too expensive to find `md` in linear time? Fear not, we can just use binary search in a reduced section of `preorder` and it works just fine :)

