solutions.content:
*Intution:* Since we have to find the complement of a given decimal number in binary form, we will use the complement property which is N + Compliment(N) = 111....111.
Foe Example : 
* N = 5 => N = 101 , Compliment(N) = 010 => 101 + 010 = 111
* N = 8 => N = 1000 , Compliment(N) = 0111 => 1000 + 0111 = 1111
* N = 17 => N = 10001, Compliment(N) = 01110 => 10001 + 01110 = 11111  and so on....

So we need to find out a number just greater than N having all 1 bits and then subtract N from it to get the complement.
Example : for N=5(101) => 111 is the number just greater than 5 having all 1s. So, 111 - 101 = 010 (Compliment)

***Approach1: (1ms)***
*Explanation:* let n = 5 and i=0, j=0
* Iteration1 : (i=0 < n) =>  i = 0 + (2^0) = 1 (1) , j = 1
* Iteration2 : (i=1 < n) =>  i = 1 + (2^1) = 3  (11) , j = 2
* Iteration3 : (i=3 < n) =>  i = 3 + (2^2) = 7 (111) , j = 3
* Iteration4 : (i=7 > n) =>  loop breaks
Compliment = i -n => 111 - 101 = 010
```

class Solution {
    public int bitwiseComplement(int n) {

        if(n==0) return 1;

        int i = 0;
        int j = 0;

        while(i<n){
            i += Math.pow(2,j);
            j++;
        }

        return i-n;
    }
}
```


***Approach2: (0ms)***
*Explanation:* Just replace the arithmetical operation into bit manipulation as i += Math.pow(2^j) can be replaced with i<<n | 1.  Let n = 5 and i=0, j=0
* Iteration1 : (i=0 < n) =>  i =0<<1 | 1 = 1 | 1 = 1
* Iteration2 : (i=1 < n) =>  i = 1<<1 | 1 = 10 | 1 = 11 = 3
* Iteration3 : (i=3 < n) =>  i = 3<<1 | 1 = 11<<1 | 1 = 110 | 1 = 111 = 7
* Iteration4 : (i=7 > n) =>  loop breaks
Compliment = i -n => 111 - 101 = 010

```
class Solution {
    public int bitwiseComplement(int n) {

        if(n==0) return 1;

        int i = 0;

        while(i<n){
            i = i<<1 | 1;
        }

        return i-n;
    }
}
```


***Approach3: (0ms)***
*Explanation:* let n = 10 and i=1, j=0
* Iteration1 : (i=1 < n) =>  i = 1 * 2 +1 = 3 (11)
* Iteration2 : (i=3 < n) =>  i = 3 * 2 + 1 = 7  (111) 
* Iteration3 : (i=7 < n) =>  i = 7 * 2 + 1 = 15 (1111)
* Iteration4 : (i=15 > n) =>  loop breaks
Compliment = i -n => 1111 - 1010 = 0101 => 101 = 5

```
class Solution {
    public int bitwiseComplement(int n) {

        int i = 1;

        while(i<n){
            i = i*2 + 1;
        }

        return i-n;
    }
}
```



*In every approach at last I am calculating compliment using i - n, which can also be done using **XOR* as *i ^n  will give the compliment*:
* i = 111 , n = 101 (5) => i ^ n = 111 ^ 101 = 010 (compliment)
* i = 1111, n = 1010 (10) => i ^ n = 1111 ^ 1010 = 0101 (compliment)


***Approach4: (0ms)*** : Using Xor Property
  In complement of n , every bit is opposite to n
* so at every place we have odd number of 1 so xor will be 1 at every place
* n^bitwiseComplement(n) =  111....1

```
Math:
a xor b = c
(a xor b) xor a = c xor a
(a xor a) xor b = c xor a
0 xor b = c xor a
b = c xor a
```

* n^111....1 =  bitwiseComplement(n)
* FInd the upper bound Number which has all 1's, Number just greater than n, will all bit 1
```
  Suppose N= 5
  X = 2+1   = 3 ,   6+1   = 7 
  X>N , X^N = 111^101 = 010
```

```
class Solution {
    public int bitwiseComplement(int n) {	     
      int X = 1;          
      while(X<n) X= X*2+1;
      return X^n;        
    }
}
```


***Approach5: (0ms)***  : Using Masking
Consider N =  10 ( 1010 )
We will start processing from right most bit (LSB) , Using **i** Variable we will we track bit , if it is set then we will unset it or vice-versa.

```
i=0 , intial bit position
if  n&1  == 0  means last bit is unset , so set it 
   result += 1<<i;
and if set then it will set to unset 

	 i++;// move to next bit position
	n >>= 1; // now move to second last bit or right shift to process next bit
```
for 0 index , it is 0   bit set to 1
for 2 index bit , it is 0 bit set to 1
**result =  1 + 100 =  0101**


```
class Solution {
    public int bitwiseComplement(int n) {

        if(n==0) return 1;

        int result = 0;
        int i = 0;        
        while(n>0){
            if((n&1) == 0){
                result += 1<<i;
            }
            i++;
            n >>= 1;
        }

        return result;
    }
}
```

