solutions.content:
> This is a complement of the other "standard solutions". If you haven't yet, go read the solution or other posts first, please.

Since this solution uses either a C++20 function `std::countl_zero()` (at this point of time, it seems even the latest GCC (10.2) hasn't implement it, Microsoft added it in VS2019 version 16.8 preview 2 just last month!) or a built-in function, please read this post just for fun. Or maybe come back in two years :)

----
### Version 1

If we have C++20:
```cpp
    return N ? ((1 << (32 - countl_zero(N))) - 1) ^ N : 1;
```
For now (gcc9), below will work:
```cpp
    return N ? ((1 << (32 - __builtin_clz(N))) - 1) ^ N : 1;
```

This version was inspired by the approach 3 from the [solution](https://leetcode.com/problems/complement-of-base-10-integer/solution/):
```java
// Java
class Solution {
    public int bitwiseComplement(int N) {
        return N == 0 ? 1 : (Integer.highestOneBit(N) << 1) - N - 1;
    }
}
```

Later I realised that it can be better!

### Version 2

```cpp
    // C++20
    return N ? (0xFFFFFFFF >> countl_zero(N)) ^ N : 1;
    // GCC9
    return N ? (0xFFFFFFFF >> __builtin_clz(N)) ^ N : 1;
```

### Version 3-beta

Now, are we able to eliminate the `ifelse`/`?:` branching?
Why not? We can just make the least significant/right most bit of the mask always 1. Easy!
```cpp
    // C++20
    return ((0xFFFFFFFF >> countl_zero(N)) | 1) ^ N;
    // GCC9 (won't work on Leetcode! See note below)
    return ((0xFFFFFFFF >> __builtin_clz(N)) | 1) ^ N;
```
Note since LeetCode OJ compiles C++ with the `-fsanitize=undefined` flag, it will throw runtime error if passing 0 to `__builtin_clz()`
But don't worry! We can tweak the input!

### Version 3

```cpp
    // C++20
    return (0xFFFFFFFF >> countl_zero(N | 1)) ^ N;
    // GCC9
    return (0xFFFFFFFF >> __builtin_clz(N | 1)) ^ N;
```
Explain: for N > 1, changing the last bit will not effect the number of leading 0s, and for both 1 and 0 we use the same mask `0x1` (ie, `0xFFFFFFFF >> 31`).

----
### Performance

So how much have we improved?
We know approach 4 from the solution (for non-premium users who can't read the solution, see reference below) is faster than any other approaches since it doesn't have any loop or call any other functions like `log()` (Note `__builtin_clz()` is a builtin function that translates to **one single CPU instruction** `BSR` (bit scan reverse))
I counted number of lines in assembly code and CPU instructions the code compiled into (GCC 10.2):

|                     | # Lines of assembly code | # CPU instructions |
| ------------- | ---------------------------- | -------------------- |
| Approach 4 |                                     25 |                           23 |
| Version 1     |                                     16 |                          14 |
| Version 2     |                                     14 |                          12 |
| Version 3     |                                       9 |                            9 |

Reference:
Approach 4:
```cpp
int bitwiseComplement(int N) {
    if (N == 0) return 1;
    int bitmask = N;
    bitmask |= (bitmask >> 1);
    bitmask |= (bitmask >> 2);
    bitmask |= (bitmask >> 4);
    bitmask |= (bitmask >> 8);
    bitmask |= (bitmask >> 16);
    return bitmask ^ N;
}
```

----
## Further thoughts

Since `std::countl_zero()` is a template, which can handle any type of integral values, can we do that as well?
Below will do:

```cpp
template <class T>
int bitwiseComplement(T N) {
    return (numeric_limits<make_unsigned<T>::type>::max() >> countl_zero(N | 1)) ^ N;
}
```
Note this requires C++20.
Since `__builtin_clz()` is only for `int` (`__builtin__clzl()` for `long` and `__builtin__clzll()` for `long long`), it'll be trickier to make it happen. That'll be too far from the scope of this problem, so I'm stopping here.

Enjoy :)

