solutions.content:
Think carefully, 5's complement(1's complement) is 2. So, 5  is 101, and 2 is 010. So, think of XOR operation. XOR is non-equality detector, if two bits are not equal, XOR bit is 1, 0 when bits are equal. So if we do 5^7, we will get 2 (101^111==010). 

### Approach : 
**Step1**:  we first need to find number of bits in 5(let say 'num'), which can be easily found by [numOfBits = (int)log2(num)+1]. 
**Step2**:  After this, we need to find number which represent 111..........numOfBits time (here we want 111 which is 7).
**Step3**: In order to find 7, we can do [ToXorWith= (2^numOfBits)-1], which can be effeciently done using binaryExponentiation.
**Step4**: now finally return 5^7 (i.e num^ToXorWith).



```
long long binaryExponentiation(long long base, long long power){
        if(power==0){ return 1; }

        long result=1;
        while(power>0){
            if(power%2==0){
                power/=2;
                base*=base;
            }
            else if(power%2==1){
                power--;
                result*=base;
            }
        }
        return result;
    }

    long long bitwiseComplement(long long n) {

        if(n==0){ return 1; }

        long long numOfBit = (long long)log2(n)+1;
        long long numToXorWith= (long long)binaryExponentiation(2,numOfBit)-1;
        return (n ^ numToXorWith);
    }
```

