solutions.content:
Let us first understand the logic through some observations.

**Observation:**
How do we know that it is a valid pair?
* We first take any (x,y) pairs.
* We add them and take the modulus with 60 and get the remainder as 0.
* Then, we will say that (x,y) are valid pairs.

A simple approach would be to iterate using two nested for loops where we will add the i+j elements where, first (i loop) and second(j loop) and take the modulus with 60. Here, the time complexity is `O(N^2)` and will lead to TLE.

**We will see an property to do this optimally :**
* Lets say we have two numbers (x,y) as a valid pair.
* We have x % 60 =R1 and y % 60=R2. 
* Now, according to the modulus property we have range of R1 and R2 to be between 0 and 60. 
* Range of R1+R2 will be 0<=R1+R2<120. For, (x+y) % 60 ==0, the possible values of R1+R2 are 0 or 60.
* We will use this remainder approach to decrease the time complexity.

**Remainder Approach :**
We will construct a remainder array to store the frequency of the remainder values .i.e., ``rem[time[i]%60]++``. The size of the array will be initialized as 60. Let's understand this by an example.

**Example:** We have 20 -> 2 times and 40 -> 3 times. Then the total pairs we can make whose sum is divisble by 60 are 6 (2 * 3). 

We find out the frequency from rem array and then we just need to make pair of rem[i] & rem[60-i].

**Here, we have two problems :**
1) We will have duplicates if we iterate the whole array. For example, If we are having 20, we will be looking for 40(60-20) as (20+40)%60==0. We will make a (20,40) pair. While looping through 40 we will search for 20 and make a (40,20) pair. Both of these pairs are same and we only need to consider one among them.

2) We have remainders 0 and 30 as special cases, where just multiplying them won't give us the result as they make pairs with themselves only.

**Solutions to the problems:**
1) We only iterate through 60/2 i.e., 30 values as from 30 it acts as a mirror and we get the duplicates.

2) We need to have more than 1 occurence of 0 and 30 to make a pair. This is given by a generalization as `(n * (n-1))/2.` For example, 5 occurences of 0 or 30 will lead to 10 pairs.

Now, lets see the implementation part:

**Java Code:**
```
class Solution {
    public int numPairsDivisibleBy60(int[] time) {
        int n=time.length;
        int[] rem=new int[60];
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        {
            rem[time[i]%60]++;
        }
        int count=0;
        count+=(rem[0]*(rem[0]-1))/2;
        count+=(rem[30]*(rem[30]-1))/2;
        for(int i=1;i<=29;i++)
        {
            count+=rem[i]*rem[60-i];
        }
        return count;
    }
}
```

**C++ Code:**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int numPairsDivisibleBy60(vector<int>& time) {

        int n=time.size();
        int rem[60]={0};
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        {
            rem[time[i]%60]++;
        }
        int count=0;
        count+=(rem[0]*(rem[0]-1))/2;
        count+=(rem[30]*(rem[30]-1))/2;
        for(int i=1;i<=29;i++)
        {
            count+=rem[i]*rem[60-i];
        }
        return count;
    }
};
```

**Time Complexity:** O(N)
where, N is the size of the time array

**Space Complexity:** O(60) or O(1)

