solutions.content:
**Intuition**
There is distributive property of ```%``` operation: ```(a + b) % c = (a % c + b % c) % c```.
So for a given time ```t```, we need to find the occurrence of ```x``` such at ```(t + x) % 60 = 0```.
According to the property, we will get ``` (t % 60 + x % 60) % 60 = 0```. 
So we can futher get either ```t % 60 + x % 60 = 0```, or ```t % 60 + x % 60 = 60```. Since ```t> 0```, so ```t % 60 + x % 60 = 0``` equals to ```t % 60 = 0``` and ```x % 60 = 0```. 
We can use Dictionary or Array to count the ocurrence of the remainders.

**why t % 60 + x % 60 = 60?**
```
(a+ b) % c = a % c + b % c = r1 + r2 
r1 < c && r2 < c
=> r1 + r2 < 2c 
If we want (r1 + r2) % c = 0, then r1 + r2 = c, 2c, 3c.... Since r1 + r2 < 2c , so r1 + r2 = c 
```


**Implemetation**
```
public class Solution {
    public int NumPairsDivisibleBy60(int[] time) {

        if(time == null || time.Length == 0)
            return 0;

        int[] remainder = new int[60];
        int cnt = 0;
        foreach(int t in time)
        {
            if(t % 60 == 0)
                cnt += remainder[0];
            else
                cnt += remainder[60 - t % 60];

            remainder[t % 60]++;
        }

        return cnt;
    }
}
```

