Brute force approach would be to try each number with the numbers right of it
```
     30 & 20
     30 & 150
     30 & 100
     30 & 40
     20 & 150 etc...
 ```

 This is not great with a list of 500 and I expect it would time out.

 So can we play around with the numbers? Does sorting help?
 Simplify the numbers? Here they are sorted and simplified
```
 [2,3,4,10,15] % 6
```

 Can we identify what a number "needs" to be moddable pair ?

*  2 needs 4
*  3 needs 3
*  4 needs 2
*  10 needs 2
*  15 needs 3

 Now I see that 15 and 10 are just more complicated 4 and 3
 We should mod those numbers by 6 and consider 
```
 [2,3,4,4,3]  % 6
```

 that looks simpler, now what? with a "x needs y" construct, an occurance count lookup map would help. which gets us
```
 {
	2: 1,
	3: 2,
	4: 2
 }
 ```
 So now I can do a O(1) look up for each number to see if a pair can be formed

*  2 needs a 4, we have two 4's so that increases our count by two
*  3 needs a 3, so every pair is a count++
*  4 we shouldn't double count, so we should set the matching count to zero in our occurance map as we find what we need.

 Enough of an idea to start coding! 

