solutions.content:
**Idea**
So the task is to find all `(n1+n2) % 60 == 0`. 
The first intuition should be if `n1 = x*60+a` and `n2 = y*60+b`, then left over parts combined `(a+b)` should be divisible by 60.
That means, imagine the corresponding remainder array `[a, b, ...]`for each element. Now, we are looking at two sum kind of problem where `target sum = 60`.

Refer https://leetcode.com/problems/two-sum/discuss/154904/Two-Java-Approaches (Basic idea for two sum is "every number will check for its partner and also adds itself to the `partners` in the hope that its future partner will find it")

There is another tricky point for this problem. All the remainders are mapped to `[0,1,2,..,59]`. So our partner pairs look like 

0+60
1+59
2+58
...
30+30

`0` is a special case as its partner `60` will never be present by definition (`modulo` wraps around at `60`). So `0` partner is not `60` in our `partners` map rather `0` itself.

```
public int numPairsDivisibleBy60(int[] times) {
        int count = 0;
        Map<Integer, Integer> partners = new HashMap<>();
        for(int time : times){
            int t = time%60;
            if(t == 0)
                count += partners.getOrDefault(t, 0);
            else
                count += partners.getOrDefault(60-t, 0);
            partners.put(t, partners.getOrDefault(t, 0)+1);
        }
        return count;
    }
```

