*Please upvote if you found this post helpful.*

For people who are questioning if we can solve this problem without knowing the property mentioned in the solution, 
Yes, we can. I only observed the pattern in the problem and came up with the following solution.

Intuition:

* Store the remainders in an array or hashmap. Hashmap takes more processing time compared to an array and since the size of the array in our case is limited (=60), array is the better option.
* Once we iterate through the given `time` array once, we will have all the remainders.
* Iterate over the remainder array to calculate the result. 
* We have 2 scenarios here.
	* The remainder is 0 or 30.
	* The remainder is any other value.
* If the remainder is 0 or 30, we basically have to see how many combinations can be formed from the remainder values. I observed that is an arithmetic series 1+2+3+..n = n(n-1)/2.
* If the remainder is not 0 or 30, we take the two sum approach and multiply (i.e) see if the `60 - x` value is availble where `x` is the remainder value.


Code:
```
class Solution {

    public int series(int n){
        return n * (n - 1) / 2;
    }
    public int numPairsDivisibleBy60(int[] time) {
        int[] arr = new int[60];

        for(int i : time){
            arr[i % 60]++;
        }

        int ans = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < 60; i++){
            if(arr[i] > 0){
                if(i == 0 || i == 30) ans += series(arr[i]);
                else if(arr[60 - i] > 0){
                    ans += arr[i] * arr[60 - i];
                    arr[i] = 0;
                }
            }

        }
        return ans;
    }
}
```

